subject: Re: [Read_Alphabet] Call of Cthulhu, through part 2
msgSnippet: I had a second look at the Wikipedia page on the guy, and, after a bit of stumbling around, happened upon this: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v4OAaiZa0dI
messageBody:
I had a second look at the Wikipedia page on the guy, and, after a bit of stumbling around, happened upon this:

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v4OAaiZa0dI

[saIm] it is.

On Jul 28, 2013, at 7:54 AM, Vincent Reilly <vin.reilly@...> wrote:

> "Sime is a surname which traces back to the Clan Fraser, and the name Shimidh, Gaelic for Simon."
> So saying it as /saim/ is arguably correct, as Sime corresponds to Simon.
>
> I love Wikipedia.
>
> On 7/28/2013 5:26 AM, Nathan Sharfi wrote:
>> Most of my free time's been spent on font work, but I've managed to post typo fixes to Github, at the usual <https://github.com/adiabatic/qs-literature>
>> . This takes me up to the end of part 2.
>>
>> How _does_ one pronounce the surname of Sidney H. Sime, though? [simE] sounds unlikely for a Briton. I'd figure [saIm], but I don't exactly trust myself in these matters…
>>
